-- tChapter 12. Environmentalism as an Arena for Political Participation in Northern Argentina -- tChapter 13. Legislating ‘Rights for Nature’ in Ecuador: The Mediated Social Construction of Human/Nature Dualisms -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aScholarship related to environmental questions in Latin America has only recently begun to coalesce around citizenship as both an empirical site of inquiry and an analytical frame of reference. This has led to a series of new insights and perspectives, but few efforts have been made to bring these various approaches into a sustained conversation across different social, temporal and geographic contexts. This volume is the result of a collaborative endeavour to advance debates on environmental citizenship, while simultaneously and systematically addressing broader theoretical and methodological questions related to the particularities of studying environment and citizenship in Latin America. Providing a window onto leading scholarship in the field, the book also sets an ambitious agenda to spark further research.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aCitizenshipzLatin America. 0aEnvironmental policyxCitizen participationzLatin America. 0aEnvironmental policyzLatin AmericaxCitizen participation. 0aEnvironmental protectionxCitizen participationzLatin America. 0aEnvironmental protectionzLatin AmericaxCitizen participation. 0aNature and civilizationzLatin America. 0aPolitical ecologyzLatin America. 0aSustainable developmentzLatin America. 7aNATURE / Environmental Conservation & Protection.2bisacsh1 aBaldwin, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCastro, Fábio de, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/rela